<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="162">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="39" type="stanza">
<l n="192">She prefaced half a hint of this </l>
<l n="193">With, &ldquo;God forbid it should be true!&rdquo; </l>
<l n="194">At the first word that Susan said </l>
<l n="195">Cried Betty, rising from the bed, </l>
<l n="196">&ldquo;Susan, I&rsquo;d gladly stay with you. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="40" type="stanza">
<l n="197">&ldquo;I must be gone, I must away, </l>
<l n="198">&ldquo;Consider, Johnny&rsquo;s but half-wise; </l>
<l n="199">&ldquo;Susan, we must take care of him, </l>
<l n="200">&ldquo;If he is hurt in life or limb&rdquo;&mdash;  </l>
<l n="201">&ldquo;Oh God forbid!&rdquo; poor Susan cries. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="41" type="stanza">
<l n="202">&ldquo;What can I do?&rdquo; says Betty, going, </l>
<l n="203">&ldquo;What can I do to ease your pain? </l>
<l n="204">&ldquo;Good Susan tell me, and I&rsquo;ll stay; </l>
<l n="205">&ldquo;I fear you&rsquo;re in a dreadful way, </l>
<l n="206">&ldquo;But I shall  soon be back again.&rdquo; </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="163">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="42" type="stanza">
<l n="207">&ldquo;Good Betty go, good Betty go, </l>
<l n="208">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s nothing that can ease my pain.&rdquo; </l>
<l n="209">Then off she hies, but with a prayer </l>
<l n="210">That God poor Susan&rsquo;s life would spare, </l>
<l n="211">Till she comes back again. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="43" type="stanza">
<l n="212">So, through the moonlight lane she goes, </l>
<l n="213">And far into the moonlight dale; </l>
<l n="214">And how she ran, and how she walked, </l>
<l n="215">And all that to herself she talked, </l>
<l n="216">Would surely be a tedious tale. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="44" type="stanza">
<l n="217">In high and low, above, below, </l>
<l n="218">In great and small, in round and square, </l>
<l n="219">In tree and tower was Johnny seen, </l>
<l n="220">In bush and brake, in black and green, </l>
<l n="221">&rsquo;Twas Johnny, Johnny, every where. </l>
