<milestone unit="page" n="165">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="48" type="stanza">
<l n="237">&ldquo;Or him that wicked pony&rsquo;s carried </l>
<l n="238">&ldquo;To the dark cave, the goblins&rsquo; hall, </l>
<l n="239">&ldquo;Or in the castle he&rsquo;s pursuing, </l>
<l n="240">&ldquo;Among the ghosts, his own undoing; </l>
<l n="241">&ldquo;Or playing with the waterfall.&rdquo; </l>
</lg>
<lg n="49" type="stanza">
<l n="242">At poor old Susan then she railed, </l>
<l n="243">While to the town she posts away; </l>
<l n="244">&ldquo;If Susan had not been so ill, </l>
<l n="245">&ldquo;Alas! I should have had him still, </l>
<l n="246">&ldquo;My Johnny, till my dying day.&rdquo; </l>
</lg>
<lg n="50" type="stanza">
<l n="247">Poor Betty! in this sad distemper, </l>
<l n="248">The doctor&rsquo;s self would hardly spare, </l>
<l n="249">Unworthy things she talked and wild, </l>
<l n="250">Even he, of cattle the most mild, </l>
<l n="251">The pony had his share. </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="166">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="51" type="stanza">
<l n="252">And now she&rsquo;s got into the town, </l>
<l n="253">And to the doctor&rsquo;s door she hies; </l>
<l n="254">&rsquo;Tis silence all on every side; </l>
<l n="255">The town so long, the town so wide, </l>
<l n="256">Is silent as the skies. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="52" type="stanza">
<l n="257">And now she&rsquo;s at the doctor&rsquo;s door, </l>
<l n="258">She lifts the knocker, rap, rap, rap, </l>
<l n="259">The doctor at the casement shews, </l>
<l n="260">His glimmering eyes that peep and doze; </l>
<l n="261">And one hand rubs his old night-cap. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="53" type="stanza">
<l n="262">&ldquo;Oh Doctor! Doctor! where&rsquo;s my Johnny?&rdquo;</l>
<l n="263">&ldquo;I&rsquo;m here, what is&rsquo;t you want with me?&rdquo; </l>
<l n="264">&ldquo;Oh Sir! you know I&rsquo;m Betty Foy, </l>
<l n="265">&ldquo;And I have lost my poor dear boy, </l>
<l n="266">&ldquo;You know him&mdash;him you often see; </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="167">
<lg n="54" type="stanza">
<l n="267">&ldquo;He&rsquo;s not so wise as some folks be,&rdquo; </l>
<l n="268">&ldquo;The devil take his wisdom!&rdquo; said </l>
<l n="269">The Doctor, looking somewhat grim, </l>
<l n="270">&ldquo;What, woman! should I know of him?&rdquo; </l>
<l n="271">And, grumbling, he went back to bed. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="55" type="stanza">
<l n="272">&ldquo;O woe is me! O woe is me! </l>
<l n="273">&ldquo;Here will I die; here will I die; </l>
<l n="274">&ldquo;I thought to find my Johnny here, </l>
<l n="275">&ldquo;But he is neither far nor near, </l>
<l n="276">&ldquo;Oh! what a wretched mother I!&rdquo; </l>
</lg>
<lg n="56" type="stanza">
<l n="277">She stops, she stands, she looks about, </l>
<l n="278">Which way to turn she cannot tell. </l>
<l n="279">Poor Betty! it would ease her pain </l>
<l n="280">If she had heart to knock again; </l>
<l n="281">&mdash;The clock strikes three&mdash;a dismal knell! </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="168">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="57" type="stanza">
<l n="282">Then up along the town she hies, </l>
<l n="283">No wonder if her senses fail,</l>
<l n="284">This piteous news so much it shock&rsquo;d her,</l>
<l n="285">She quite forgot to send the Doctor, </l>
<l n="286">To comfort poor old Susan Gale. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="58" type="stanza">
<l n="287">And now she&rsquo;s high upon the down, </l>
<l n="288">And she can see a mile of road, </l>
<l n="289">&ldquo;Oh cruel! I&rsquo;m almost three-score; </l>
<l n="290">&ldquo;Such night as this was ne&rsquo;er before, </l>
<l n="291">&ldquo;There&rsquo;s not a single soul abroad.&rdquo; </l>
</lg>
<lg n="59" type="stanza">
<l n="292">She listens, but she cannot hear </l>
<l n="293">The foot of horse, the voice of man; </l>
<l n="294">The streams with softest sound are flowing,</l>
<l n="295">The grass you almost hear it growing, </l>
<l n="296">You hear it now if e&rsquo;er you can. </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="169">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="60" type="stanza">
<l n="297">The owlets through the long blue night </l>
<l n="298">Are shouting to each other still: </l>
<l n="299">Fond lovers, yet not quite hob nob, </l>
<l n="300">They lengthen out the tremulous sob, </l>
<l n="301">That echoes far from hill to hill. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="61" type="stanza">
<l n="302">Poor Betty now has lost all hope, </l>
<l n="303">Her thoughts are bent on deadly sin; </l>
<l n="304">A green-grown pond she just has pass&rsquo;d, </l>
<l n="305">And from the brink she hurries fast, </l>
<l n="306">Lest she should drown herself therein. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="62" type="stanza">
<l n="307">And now she sits her down and weeps; </l>
<l n="308">Such tears she never shed before; </l>
<l n="309">&ldquo;Oh dear, dear pony! my sweet joy! </l>
<l n="310">&ldquo;Oh carry back my idiot boy! </l>
<l n="311">&ldquo;And we will ne&rsquo;er o&rsquo;erload thee more.&rdquo;</l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="170">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="63" type="stanza">
<l n="312">A thought is come into her head; </l>
<l n="313">&ldquo;The pony he is mild and good, </l>
<l n="314">&ldquo;And we have always used him well; </l>
<l n="315">&ldquo;Perhaps he&rsquo;s gone along the dell, </l>
<l n="316">&ldquo;And carried Johnny to the wood.&rdquo;</l>
</lg>
<lg n="64" type="stanza">
<l n="317">Then up she springs as if on wings; </l>
<l n="318">She thinks no more of deadly sin; </l>
<l n="319">If Betty fifty ponds should see, </l>
<l n="320">The last of all her thoughts would be,</l>
<l n="321">To drown herself therein. </l>
