<l n="361">Sits upright on a feeding horse? </l>
</lg>
<lg n="73" type="stanza">
<l n="362">Unto his horse, that&rsquo;s feeding free, </l>
<l n="363">He seems, I think, the rein to give; </l>
<l n="364">Of moon or stars he takes no heed; </l>
<l n="365">Of such we in romances read, </l>
<l n="366"> &mdash;&rsquo;Tis Johnny! Johnny! as I live. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="74" type="stanza">
<l n="367">And that&rsquo;s the very pony too.</l>
<l n="368">Where is she, where is Betty Foy? </l>
<l n="369">She hardly can sustain her fears; </l>
<l n="370">The roaring water-fall she hears, </l>
<l n="371">And cannot find her idiot boy. </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="174">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="75" type="stanza">
<l n="372">Your pony&rsquo;s worth his weight in gold, </l>
<l n="373">Then calm your terrors, Betty Foy! </l>
<l n="374">She&rsquo;s coming from among the trees, </l>
<l n="375">And now, all full in view, she sees </l>
<l n="376">Him whom she loves, her idiot boy. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="76" type="stanza">
<l n="377">And Betty sees the pony too: </l>
<l n="378">Why stand you thus Good Betty Foy? </l>
<l n="379">It is no goblin, &rsquo;tis no ghost, </l>
<l n="380">&rsquo;Tis he whom you so long have lost, </l>
<l n="381">He whom you love, your idiot boy. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="77" type="stanza">
<l n="382">She looks again&mdash;her arms are up&mdash;  </l>
<l n="383">She screams&mdash;she cannot move for joy; </l>
<l n="384">She darts as with a torrent&rsquo;s force, </l>
<l n="385">She has almost o&rsquo;erturned the horse, </l>
<l n="386">And fast she holds her idiot boy. </l>
</lg>
<pb>
<milestone unit="page" n="175">
<lb>
<lb>
<lg n="78" type="stanza">
<l n="387">And Johnny burrs and laughs aloud, </l>
<l n="388">Whether in cunning or in joy, </l>
<l n="389">I cannot tell; but while he laughs, </l>
<l n="390">Betty a drunken pleasure quaffs, </l>
<l n="391">To hear again her idiot boy. </l>
</lg>
<lg n="79" type="stanza">
<l n="392">And now she&rsquo;s at the pony&rsquo;s tail,</l>
<l n="393">And now she&rsquo;s at the pony&rsquo;s head, </l>
<l n="394">On that side now, and now on this, </l>
<l n="395">And almost stifled with her bliss, </l>
<l n="396">A few sad tears does Betty shed.</l>
</lg>
<lg n="80" type="stanza">
<l n="397">She kisses o&rsquo;er and o&rsquo;er again, </l>
<l n="398">Him whom she loves, her idiot boy, </l>
<l n="399">She&rsquo;s happy here, she&rsquo;s happy there, </l>
<l n="400">She is uneasy every where;</l>
